So Chef Carmellini has trained throughout
the

00:00:22.179 --> 00:00:24.440
great restaurants of Italy and New York from
Michelin

00:00:24.440 --> 00:00:30.589
two star San Dominico in Emilia-Romagna to
Lespinasse to Le Cirque in New York.

00:00:30.589 --> 00:00:34.149
He spent six years
at c Café Boulud winning a James Beard Award

00:00:34.149 --> 00:00:37.250
for rising star
chef of the year, and was added to Food and

00:00:37.250 --> 00:00:39.829
Wine magazine's Best
Chef roster.

00:00:39.829 --> 00:00:44.860
In his last month at Café Boulud, he was
awarded best chef New York City by the James

00:00:44.860 --> 00:00:46.800
Beard
Foundation.

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:51.940
He then went onto open A Voce in 2006 earning
a three star review from the New York Times.

00:00:51.940 --> 00:00:56.700
His first
Michelin star and a James Beard Award nomination

00:00:56.700 --> 00:00:59.679
for Best Restaurant in
2007.

00:00:59.679 --> 00:01:02.550
And in 2008 he published his first book of
recipes

00:01:02.550 --> 00:01:05.290
and stories with his wife, Urban Italian.

00:01:05.290 --> 00:01:08.540
And his second
cookbook, American Flavor, just came out this

00:01:08.540 --> 00:01:11.960
week -- which, hopefully, you all
got in the audience.

00:01:11.960 --> 00:01:15.080
Chef Carmellini also owns two
highly-celebrated restaurants.

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:18.340
One of my personal
favorites in New York, Locanda Verde, that's

00:01:18.340 --> 00:01:21.369
just my plug to get a table, in the Greenwich
Hotel in Tribeca.

00:01:21.369 --> 00:01:22.369
&gt;&gt;Andrew: It works.

00:01:22.369 --> 00:01:23.369
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: It does work.

00:01:23.369 --> 00:01:24.369
I know.

00:01:24.369 --> 00:01:25.369
It's all up here.

00:01:25.369 --> 00:01:27.790
And that has two
stars from the New York Times and was also

00:01:27.790 --> 00:01:30.369
nominated by
the James Beard Foundation for Best New Restaurant

00:01:30.369 --> 00:01:31.369
in
2009.

00:01:31.369 --> 00:01:32.429
&gt;&gt; Andrew: They like me.

00:01:32.429 --> 00:01:33.429
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: They do.

00:01:33.429 --> 00:01:34.640
What's with that foundation?

00:01:34.640 --> 00:01:37.590
And also the Dutch in Soho and he's opening
a second

00:01:37.590 --> 00:01:40.159
location of the Dutch in just a couple of
weeks.

00:01:40.159 --> 00:01:41.159
.
&gt;&gt; Andrew: Next month.

00:01:41.159 --> 00:01:42.479
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: Next month so there you go.

00:01:42.479 --> 00:01:44.110
And he's very busy.

00:01:44.110 --> 00:01:46.470
And we're excited
that you made time to come here to Google,

00:01:46.470 --> 00:01:47.470
so thank you
for that.

00:01:47.470 --> 00:01:48.470
&gt;&gt; Andrew: Thanks for having me.

00:01:48.470 --> 00:01:49.470
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: It's a pleasure.

00:01:49.470 --> 00:01:52.610
And you obviously have this
incredible laundry list of accomplishments.

00:01:52.610 --> 00:01:54.430
So I thought
we'd just go over them one by one.

00:01:54.430 --> 00:01:55.909
&gt;&gt; Andrew: No, that's sounds awful.

00:01:55.909 --> 00:01:59.750
[laughter]
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: Like I say, how did you get

00:01:59.750 --> 00:02:01.909
into cooking?

00:02:01.909 --> 00:02:06.070
&gt;&gt; Andrew: You know I was either going to
be a rock star or I was

00:02:06.070 --> 00:02:07.509
going to be a chef.

00:02:07.509 --> 00:02:12.050
You know, in the late -- I've
started cooking when just kind of this is

00:02:12.050 --> 00:02:14.110
a little bit
cliché but I just started cooking with my

00:02:14.110 --> 00:02:15.280
mom, my grandmother.

00:02:15.280 --> 00:02:17.510
I really liked it.

00:02:17.510 --> 00:02:22.129
In the 70s when I grew up, you know,
there was that whole health food thing going

00:02:22.129 --> 00:02:23.129
on.

00:02:23.129 --> 00:02:26.450
You
know, there was carob and wheat germ and my

00:02:26.450 --> 00:02:28.390
mom was
kind of into that.

00:02:28.390 --> 00:02:30.670
They didn't want to eat process
foods.

00:02:30.670 --> 00:02:32.470
They just liked good food.

00:02:32.470 --> 00:02:34.140
We had a garden in
the back.

00:02:34.140 --> 00:02:36.860
This was long before the word foodie existed.

00:02:36.860 --> 00:02:42.610
There wasn't that hyper restaurant culture,
chef culture

00:02:42.610 --> 00:02:45.310
that exists today, which is great.

00:02:45.310 --> 00:02:47.110
They just wanted good food.

00:02:47.110 --> 00:02:53.129
And they
were big influences on me to get me into cooking.

00:02:53.129 --> 00:02:55.330
I was
also a musician.

00:02:55.330 --> 00:02:59.019
I was either going to go to a school of music
or I was going to go to cooking school.

00:02:59.019 --> 00:03:01.629
And I'm
not sure -- still to this day -- why I went

00:03:01.629 --> 00:03:04.120
to cooking
school besides I'm actually glad I didn't

00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:06.990
go to music
school back then because it was 1989.

00:03:06.990 --> 00:03:10.020
It was pre-Grunge
and hair was very long still.

00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:11.549
[Interviewer giggles] And I'm glad I didn't
go

00:03:11.549 --> 00:03:15.260
that route, [chuckles] because who knows what
would happen today.

00:03:15.260 --> 00:03:18.680
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: Was there one dish that inspired
your love of food in

00:03:18.680 --> 00:03:20.950
maybe the carob and the kale.

00:03:20.950 --> 00:03:21.950
&gt;&gt; No.

00:03:21.950 --> 00:03:22.950
No carob.

00:03:22.950 --> 00:03:27.490
[laughter] You know, I used to like baking
too

00:03:27.490 --> 00:03:30.470
when I was a kid just because I had a crazy
sweet tooth.

00:03:30.470 --> 00:03:31.620
And still today.

00:03:31.620 --> 00:03:35.650
That's why I'm blessed with two amazing
pastry chefs at both restaurants.

00:03:35.650 --> 00:03:38.680
That's mostly for my
own satisfaction.

00:03:38.680 --> 00:03:43.200
But you know, I just really liked
cherry pie.

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:45.470
[chuckles] That was like you know I grew up
in the

00:03:45.470 --> 00:03:49.780
Midwest and it's kind of like that iconic.

00:03:49.780 --> 00:03:52.720
You know it's
just something very satisfying about it.

00:03:52.720 --> 00:03:56.950
That's why
Dutch that restaurant was built just for pie.

00:03:56.950 --> 00:04:01.090
At the
time no one was doing pies anymore.

00:04:01.090 --> 00:04:03.969
And so, that was a
big inspiration behind it.

00:04:03.969 --> 00:04:07.260
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: So what was your inspiration
for the book -- for the

00:04:07.260 --> 00:04:08.260
new book?

00:04:08.260 --> 00:04:10.849
&gt;&gt; Andrew: You know the book it's not a restaurant
cookbook like

00:04:10.849 --> 00:04:13.879
Urban Italian my first cook book.

00:04:13.879 --> 00:04:19.090
I have 500 plus cook
books around the world.

00:04:19.090 --> 00:04:22.350
They're not chef cookbooks even
though I'm a chef.

00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:26.600
My wife Gwen Hyman wrote the book
Urban Italian with me.

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:33.760
That process for us is in our New York
City apartment kitchen, she is on her laptop

00:04:33.760 --> 00:04:38.410
sitting next
to me and I am in the kitchen and we make

00:04:38.410 --> 00:04:40.020
every single
recipe together.

00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:46.690
And, since she's not a chef, she needs
to measure things and she doesn't have that

00:04:46.690 --> 00:04:48.780
kind of
instinct to just kind of throw something together.

00:04:48.780 --> 00:04:51.550
So
she is making me -- she wants to make sure

00:04:51.550 --> 00:04:54.070
that anyone
can make that.

00:04:54.070 --> 00:04:57.920
Or when you make it or I make it or
someone else makes it it's going to work.

00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:02.050
So that's kind
of both books really -- they're not restaurant

00:05:02.050 --> 00:05:07.740
cookbooks,
but they tell a story of what's influenced

00:05:07.740 --> 00:05:10.610
me over the
years or just what kind of gets me cooking

00:05:10.610 --> 00:05:11.610
really.

00:05:11.610 --> 00:05:14.420
And
so, you know American flavor really is that

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:16.230
kind of
journey of being American chef.

00:05:16.230 --> 00:05:22.260
It's a little bit like I
think chefs born in America are kind of afraid

00:05:22.260 --> 00:05:25.690
to use
that word like I'm American chef.

00:05:25.690 --> 00:05:28.930
It's a little bit
of -- I don't know it's not flattering in

00:05:28.930 --> 00:05:29.930
some ways or I
think.

00:05:29.930 --> 00:05:30.930
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: Why do you think that.

00:05:30.930 --> 00:05:31.930
&gt;&gt;Andrew: I don't know.

00:05:31.930 --> 00:05:37.860
I just think that American cooking --
we're not blessed with thousand years of history

00:05:37.860 --> 00:05:40.510
like
France or China in that term.

00:05:40.510 --> 00:05:46.930
And so American cooking --
I think American cooking now -- the modern

00:05:46.930 --> 00:05:52.480
kind of look
at it -- it's a combination of all this kind

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:54.690
of
root-inspired cooking.

00:05:54.690 --> 00:05:57.470
It's kind of like what your
grandmother was cooking, what my grandmother

00:05:57.470 --> 00:05:59.000
was cooking
but not mixed.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:02.400
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: [chuckling] Probably not what
my grandmother was cooking.

00:06:02.400 --> 00:06:03.890
&gt;&gt; Andrew: What was that actually?

00:06:03.890 --> 00:06:05.790
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: She wasn't doing a lot of
the cooking probably.

00:06:05.790 --> 00:06:06.790
That's part of it.

00:06:06.790 --> 00:06:10.420
I think her daughter-in-law including
my mother were probably doing it.

00:06:10.420 --> 00:06:15.070
It was Indian stuff but in India
so not in America.

00:06:15.070 --> 00:06:18.640
&gt;&gt;Andrew: But still that influence with your
cooking at home

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:19.640
that's what?

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:20.970
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: It's Italian food.

00:06:20.970 --> 00:06:21.970
But I'm Indian.

00:06:21.970 --> 00:06:23.550
I know, it
doesn't make any sense.

00:06:23.550 --> 00:06:25.570
&gt;&gt;Andrew: My grandmother was Italian, but
she.

00:06:25.570 --> 00:06:26.630
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: Made Indian food?

00:06:26.630 --> 00:06:28.440
That would be weird.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:32.550
&gt;&gt;Andrew: That would be really strange.

00:06:32.550 --> 00:06:37.750
They were in Miami in
the 30s, 40s and 50s and Miami back then was

00:06:37.750 --> 00:06:39.250
a southern
town.

00:06:39.250 --> 00:06:42.150
It was kind of like Mobile, Alabama more than
it

00:06:42.150 --> 00:06:43.480
is kind of the Miami today.

00:06:43.480 --> 00:06:48.080
And so, they would -- you
know, she was Italian, but she eventually

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:52.570
was cooking up
until she passed away on New Year's Eve she

00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:56.360
would cook
beans and black-eyed peas and she would cook

00:06:56.360 --> 00:06:57.360
biscuits and
she would make pies.

00:06:57.360 --> 00:07:02.770
And so, you know, we have that kind
of -- both those things going on at the same

00:07:02.770 --> 00:07:03.770
time.

00:07:03.770 --> 00:07:06.640
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Yeah, my mother would make
Indian food with oregano

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:09.190
which is not a traditional Indian spice.

00:07:09.190 --> 00:07:10.190
&gt;&gt; Andrew: Interesting.

00:07:10.190 --> 00:07:11.190
Like dahl with oregano.

00:07:11.190 --> 00:07:13.760
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: They didn't get all the spices
here.

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:15.389
&gt;&gt; Andrew: It's very fusion.

00:07:15.389 --> 00:07:18.030
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: She was fusion before fusion
was fusion.

00:07:18.030 --> 00:07:20.479
&gt;&gt; Andrew: She's a really trend setter.

00:07:20.479 --> 00:07:23.330
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: Yeah, she was a foodie back
then.

00:07:23.330 --> 00:07:26.970
[chuckles] And so, about the
book, what's your favorite recipe in the book

00:07:26.970 --> 00:07:29.250
or do you
have a favorite recipe.

00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:31.900
&gt;&gt; Andrew: Kind of like the menus at both
restaurants, I like to

00:07:31.900 --> 00:07:34.170
have something for everybody.

00:07:34.170 --> 00:07:37.610
And so, it kind of just
depends what you're in the mood for really.

00:07:37.610 --> 00:07:40.230
You know, so
it could be something like there's a lot of

00:07:40.230 --> 00:07:42.971
vegetables
inside the book, but there's also what I would

00:07:42.971 --> 00:07:46.530
say is
like a ridiculous over the top American dish

00:07:46.530 --> 00:07:52.210
which is --
it's a barbecued meatloaf that has macaroni

00:07:52.210 --> 00:07:54.120
and cheese
stuffed inside it [laughter].

00:07:54.120 --> 00:07:55.800
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: That sounds awesome.

00:07:55.800 --> 00:07:57.480
&gt;&gt; Andrew: Which is like.

00:07:57.480 --> 00:07:59.710
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: That's so wrong, it's right.

00:07:59.710 --> 00:08:02.490
&gt;&gt; Andrew: It's one of those dishes that's
like so wrong it's

00:08:02.490 --> 00:08:03.490
right.

00:08:03.490 --> 00:08:11.530
So I have -- you know, there's a dish of organic
red quinoa with wild rice and pecans and some

00:08:11.530 --> 00:08:13.680
other stuff
and then there's also.

00:08:13.680 --> 00:08:15.310
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: Whiskey I believe is in there.

00:08:15.310 --> 00:08:16.310
&gt;&gt; Andrew: Whiskey.

00:08:16.310 --> 00:08:20.910
It's healthy and not healthy at the same
time because it's all about balance.

00:08:20.910 --> 00:08:23.410
But I don't know --
the meatloaf thing is fun because it's kind

00:08:23.410 --> 00:08:25.340
of a cool
thing you can totally do at home and then

00:08:25.340 --> 00:08:28.260
bring it to the table
and cut it and people are going to be like,

00:08:28.260 --> 00:08:29.260
"Whoa!"

00:08:29.260 --> 00:08:30.560
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: "What's happening?"

00:08:30.560 --> 00:08:32.860
So what's the technique?

00:08:32.860 --> 00:08:35.880
You
know, you just kind of make the macaroni then

00:08:35.880 --> 00:08:39.880
you roll it
into kind of like log and then put it in the

00:08:39.880 --> 00:08:42.880
freezer and
then you make your meatloaf and then you take

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:45.280
out the
frozen log and you kind of wrap it around

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:46.280
it.

00:08:46.280 --> 00:08:47.770
You bake
it you glaze it with this homemade barbecue

00:08:47.770 --> 00:08:50.800
sauce and it
has some other stuff in it too, but it works

00:08:50.800 --> 00:08:54.570
out with the
temperature of the macaroni and cheese just

00:08:54.570 --> 00:08:56.900
oozes out perfectly as
the meatloaf is cooked.

00:08:56.900 --> 00:08:58.040
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: That sounds so good; I'm really
hungry.

00:08:58.040 --> 00:08:59.476
I know I should not have skipped breakfast
this morning.

00:08:59.476 --> 00:09:01.390
&gt;&gt; Andrew: It's kind of like molecular gastronomy
with no

00:09:01.390 --> 00:09:02.390
chemicals.

00:09:02.390 --> 00:09:04.140
It's just about temperature.

00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:05.670
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: That's awesome.

00:09:05.670 --> 00:09:07.950
And so, obviously we're here in New
York.

00:09:07.950 --> 00:09:10.040
And you mentioned your tiny New York kitchen
which

00:09:10.040 --> 00:09:12.580
many of us share that challenge.

00:09:12.580 --> 00:09:15.670
What do you recommend
from the book is easy enough to make in a

00:09:15.670 --> 00:09:16.890
tiny New York
kitchen?

00:09:16.890 --> 00:09:19.750
Can you make meatloaf stuffed with macaroni
and

00:09:19.750 --> 00:09:20.750
cheese?

00:09:20.750 --> 00:09:26.691
&gt;&gt; Andrew: Again, I made everything in my
kitchen and so I tried

00:09:26.691 --> 00:09:29.090
to like maybe -- I remember with Urban Italian,
my first

00:09:29.090 --> 00:09:32.210
book, I'm fortunate enough at the restaurant
that I don't

00:09:32.210 --> 00:09:33.510
have to do dishes anymore.

00:09:33.510 --> 00:09:36.110
When I first started in the
restaurant business, I was definitely washing

00:09:36.110 --> 00:09:37.110
dishes.

00:09:37.110 --> 00:09:39.080
And
you have to remember that when you're a chef

00:09:39.080 --> 00:09:42.350
for a lot of
years it was always -- I was cooking at home

00:09:42.350 --> 00:09:44.020
and it was
15 pots.

00:09:44.020 --> 00:09:45.030
You want to do this you want to do that.

00:09:45.030 --> 00:09:47.770
We
try to make with the home versions of everything,

00:09:47.770 --> 00:09:50.950
I try
to do everything with one or two pots or one

00:09:50.950 --> 00:09:53.450
pot and a
pan you know so you don't have to -- that's

00:09:53.450 --> 00:09:55.890
the worst you
make the whole dinner and you have to deal

00:09:55.890 --> 00:09:56.890
with the clean
up afterwards.

00:09:56.890 --> 00:09:58.440
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: That's what my husband's for
&gt;&gt;Andrew: Clean up as you go.

00:09:58.440 --> 00:09:59.440
It's really
important.

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:00.790
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: Clean up as you go.

00:10:00.790 --> 00:10:04.320
Or have a husband who will do dishes who's
so

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:05.580
particular about cleanliness.

00:10:05.580 --> 00:10:08.279
&gt;&gt; Andrew: You're very gendered about these
things.

00:10:08.279 --> 00:10:12.860
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: That's true, because I do
the cooking and he does the

00:10:12.860 --> 00:10:13.860
cleaning.

00:10:13.860 --> 00:10:14.860
It's a good division of labor.

00:10:14.860 --> 00:10:16.520
Sometimes cooking involves ordering
&gt;&gt; Andrew: That's good.

00:10:16.520 --> 00:10:18.680
I would take that role if you cooked for
me every night.

00:10:18.680 --> 00:10:19.780
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: Or order.

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:22.900
I can call up with the best of them.

00:10:22.900 --> 00:10:25.040
Tell
us more about the restaurants speaking about

00:10:25.040 --> 00:10:26.040
those.

00:10:26.040 --> 00:10:28.890
Locanda Verde and The Dutch; how did they
come about?

00:10:28.890 --> 00:10:33.140
--
&gt;&gt; Andrew: Locanda Verde is -- originally

00:10:33.140 --> 00:10:36.770
I was going to open up
a little pasta bar on Tenth Street between

00:10:36.770 --> 00:10:37.770
Second and
Third.

00:10:37.770 --> 00:10:43.440
And Bob DeNiro has the Greenwich Hotel and
they were having some problems there with

00:10:43.440 --> 00:10:47.110
the restaurant there And I started talking
to them

00:10:47.110 --> 00:10:48.860
about doing something there and that's kind
of how

00:10:48.860 --> 00:10:50.130
Locanda came to be.

00:10:50.130 --> 00:10:52.730
And I just wanted like Locanda Verde
and the Dutch really.

00:10:52.730 --> 00:10:58.480
Because for a long time I did
really high-end French and Italian food uptown

00:10:58.480 --> 00:11:01.900
and it was
great and I like that to be able to give people

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:04.460
that
experience but I always lived downtown but

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:05.880
I was always
working uptown.

00:11:05.880 --> 00:11:11.980
And I just -- you know, for me in my
ripe old age of 35 when I did Locanda Verde,

00:11:11.980 --> 00:11:14.900
I just
wanted restaurant, a corner New York City

00:11:14.900 --> 00:11:17.800
restaurant you
could stop by any time of day.

