00:14:09.610 --> 00:14:12.420
the farmer's market
measurably.

00:14:12.420 --> 00:14:14.980
Is there any culinary mountain that you want
to climb?

00:14:14.980 --> 00:14:20.110
Like something you've always wanted to do?

00:14:20.110 --> 00:14:23.050
&gt;&gt;Andrew: Culinary mountain.

00:14:23.050 --> 00:14:26.820
You know, I'd like to to do a
French restaurant one day.

00:14:26.820 --> 00:14:31.290
You know, French food kind of
like -- American food -- the idea of American

00:14:31.290 --> 00:14:35.300
food it's
just like especially French because it's a

00:14:35.300 --> 00:14:37.040
little bit out
of fashion a little bit.

00:14:37.040 --> 00:14:42.960
And I kind of want -- I love, I
mean France it's such an amazing culinary

00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:45.460
journey really
in all the different regions.

00:14:45.460 --> 00:14:49.480
And I kind of want to
revisit that and do that one day.

00:14:49.480 --> 00:14:51.310
Probably not on a
super high-end level.

00:14:51.310 --> 00:14:52.750
Probably approachable level.

00:14:52.750 --> 00:14:56.000
But I
want to kind of get back to the country that

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.770
first kind
of inspired me with cooking which is France

00:14:58.770 --> 00:14:59.770
at first even
before Italy.

00:14:59.770 --> 00:15:02.580
And so, yeah I would like to do something
French.

00:15:02.580 --> 00:15:05.640
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: All right.

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:14.370
Are there any unexpected influences in
your cuisine?

00:15:14.370 --> 00:15:19.770
&gt;&gt; Andrew: You know for example there's an
Indian technique

00:15:19.770 --> 00:15:24.360
called tarka where you kind of will heat up
ghee and then

00:15:24.360 --> 00:15:26.500
kind of bloom spices in it.

00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:31.250
Sometimes mustard seeds and
it's interesting to take like that technique

00:15:31.250 --> 00:15:36.230
and apply it
to a sauce from someone else or some other

00:15:36.230 --> 00:15:38.870
kind of
country but it's not fusion necessarily.

00:15:38.870 --> 00:15:44.460
So for example,
if you were to make like a 'sauce mutard'

00:15:44.460 --> 00:15:47.430
or a mustard
sauce typical with fish or meat.

00:15:47.430 --> 00:15:51.220
In French cooking,
you -- the way to approach that really is,

00:15:51.220 --> 00:15:55.690
you take that
technique of tarka and taking mustard seeds

00:15:55.690 --> 00:15:58.530
and kind of
blooming them a little bit and making them

00:15:58.530 --> 00:16:00.510
pop.

00:16:00.510 --> 00:16:02.260
And
then, doing that with maybe a French sauce.

00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:05.560
So you're
not really again it's not fusion in the sense

00:16:05.560 --> 00:16:09.460
you're
mixing curry powder with mustard with, you

00:16:09.460 --> 00:16:11.540
know, some
kind of French preparation.

00:16:11.540 --> 00:16:14.930
It's more like taking this
particular technique and applying to a sauce

00:16:14.930 --> 00:16:16.630
and making
it even better even though it comes from another

00:16:16.630 --> 00:16:20.130
culture
which is kind of interesting.

00:16:20.130 --> 00:16:24.110
For example, like the
French sauce you might have your glace de

00:16:24.110 --> 00:16:27.930
viande and you might add
some reduced cream to it and finish it with

00:16:27.930 --> 00:16:29.470
Dijon
mustard.

00:16:29.470 --> 00:16:36.940
Here you can take the tarka and make those
mustard seeds pop in the hot ghee.

00:16:36.940 --> 00:16:39.950
We might not use hot
ghee for that sauce.

00:16:39.950 --> 00:16:42.200
We might just use butter.

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:45.630
And then add
your glace de viande . So I look at food that

00:16:45.630 --> 00:16:46.630
way sometimes.

00:16:46.630 --> 00:16:52.440
In
the balance sweet and sour in Thai food or

00:16:52.440 --> 00:16:53.440
Vietnamese
food.

00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:54.920
You can apply to Italian food.

00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:58.810
Not that you can
use fish sauce in Italian food but just balsamic

00:16:58.810 --> 00:17:02.010
vinegar
and olive oil.

00:17:02.010 --> 00:17:04.680
I kind of look for parallels that way.

