00:21:10.549 --> 00:21:13.790
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: So what do you think of the
whole molecular

00:21:13.790 --> 00:21:15.450
gastronomy trend.

00:21:15.450 --> 00:21:18.650
Your food is so much more like rustic.

00:21:18.650 --> 00:21:23.040
I
think of it as rustic almost like home cooking

00:21:23.040 --> 00:21:25.970
but
obviously elevated but there's something very

00:21:25.970 --> 00:21:27.539
approachable I guess about it.

00:21:27.539 --> 00:21:31.100
&gt;&gt; Andrew: You know, I had bring up ElBulli
that's one of the stories in

00:21:31.100 --> 00:21:32.100
American flavor.

00:21:32.100 --> 00:21:38.679
I, in 1996 I was working at France and
after a year I took three months off and just

00:21:38.679 --> 00:21:39.980
traveled.

00:21:39.980 --> 00:21:43.280
And a couple chefs said go down to Spain check
this guy

00:21:43.280 --> 00:21:46.580
out, check this guy out, and I went.

00:21:46.580 --> 00:21:52.140
I went by myself and
I was the only person there for lunch.

00:21:52.140 --> 00:21:55.070
And you know, I
was 25.

00:21:55.070 --> 00:21:56.960
I didn't really know what I was getting into.

00:21:56.960 --> 00:21:59.600
I
thought I was going to have paella and pan

00:21:59.600 --> 00:22:06.030
con tomate all this kind of
classic kettle and dishes and I sat down and

00:22:06.030 --> 00:22:11.410
we had 20 amuse-bouche
and there was all this stuff going on.

00:22:11.410 --> 00:22:12.559
Interviewer: Forty courses later --
Andrew: And it was

00:22:12.559 --> 00:22:14.080
like a 35 course lunch.

00:22:14.080 --> 00:22:21.220
And it wasn't -- it was cooking
I never seen anything like it before.

00:22:21.220 --> 00:22:24.780
And so, I asked
can I see the chef.

00:22:24.780 --> 00:22:27.910
In my mind for some reason I thought
it was going to be a couple -- because I was

00:22:27.910 --> 00:22:30.190
the only
customer I thought it would be just a couple

00:22:30.190 --> 00:22:32.549
of guys in
the kitchen hanging out.

00:22:32.549 --> 00:22:35.761
And the glass doors open there was 40 people
back there.

00:22:35.761 --> 00:22:36.761
There were sculptures
inside.

00:22:36.761 --> 00:22:41.450
The first thing I noticed there were no ovens
inside the kitchen.

00:22:41.450 --> 00:22:44.830
And I was like, "What is this
place?"

00:22:44.830 --> 00:22:48.320
And so, I met Ferran and he was lovely.

00:22:48.320 --> 00:22:51.130
And I
said, "Well, I'm not doing anything for the

00:22:51.130 --> 00:22:53.350
rest of the
summer can I just stay here and work?"

00:22:53.350 --> 00:22:55.350
He said, "I have
too many people here.

00:22:55.350 --> 00:22:58.410
I'll tell you what, come back for lunch.

00:22:58.410 --> 00:23:02.550
I could even I couldn't even afford
the the gas to get back to Rosas.

00:23:02.550 --> 00:23:03.929
And at that point.

00:23:03.929 --> 00:23:08.190
He's like no no please come for lunch with
my guest.

00:23:08.190 --> 00:23:11.559
I took
him up on it and I slept in the car and in

00:23:11.559 --> 00:23:14.700
the morning I
took swim and put on my clothes from the day

00:23:14.700 --> 00:23:19.500
before and
went for lunch and he had put a table in the

00:23:19.500 --> 00:23:22.570
kitchen for
two people.

00:23:22.570 --> 00:23:27.299
And he was the second person and another 40
courses completely different from the day

00:23:27.299 --> 00:23:28.299
before came out.

00:23:28.299 --> 00:23:29.299
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: That's amazing.

00:23:29.299 --> 00:23:32.049
&gt;&gt;Andrew: And he sat down and ate every one
with me and we just

00:23:32.049 --> 00:23:34.820
talked about food and what he was trying to
do.

00:23:34.820 --> 00:23:38.559
This is
kind of before he really had that international

00:23:38.559 --> 00:23:41.580
fame and
started working with the chemicals and trying

00:23:41.580 --> 00:23:45.160
to change
the perception of the diner and change that

00:23:45.160 --> 00:23:48.910
kind of
