00:36:11.260 --> 00:36:14.739
home it's just again that old technique of
just picking

00:36:14.739 --> 00:36:16.920
it up and then when the juices are clear and
it doesn't

00:36:16.920 --> 00:36:20.859
have the little blood specks in it, it's good
to go.

00:36:20.859 --> 00:36:21.859
Yeah.

00:36:21.859 --> 00:36:24.160
&gt;&gt; Female #1: Nice.

00:36:24.160 --> 00:36:26.640
&gt;&gt; Female #2: Yeah.

00:36:26.640 --> 00:36:30.339
I was wondering, you know, so much of a
restaurant in New York is the ambiance.

00:36:30.339 --> 00:36:33.310
How involved are
you in the decorations of the restaurant and

00:36:33.310 --> 00:36:36.749
the plating
how does that whole process work.

00:36:36.749 --> 00:36:42.220
&gt;&gt; Andrew: We have two great designers at
both restaurants.

00:36:42.220 --> 00:36:45.469
Probably I micromanage too much with my partners
on how

00:36:45.469 --> 00:36:46.469
that gets done.

00:36:46.469 --> 00:36:51.910
I know at both restaurants the art
that's on the wall, the photographs, the kind

00:36:51.910 --> 00:36:56.900
of random
object that's here and there I bought myself.

00:36:56.900 --> 00:36:59.589
I know
over at the Dutch I probably started like

00:36:59.589 --> 00:37:02.059
two years ago
just kind of collecting things because we

00:37:02.059 --> 00:37:05.739
had this idea
of what we wanted to do exactly.

00:37:05.739 --> 00:37:09.109
So it's
combination of some Internet finds a trip

00:37:09.109 --> 00:37:14.079
to up state
here and there, just kind of, you know, Brooklyn

00:37:14.079 --> 00:37:16.059
Flea and
Chelsea Market.

00:37:16.059 --> 00:37:23.469
Just kind of like to help tell a
story -- because it's the corner restaurant.

00:37:23.469 --> 00:37:25.480
Both are
corner restaurants, I wanted to have that

00:37:25.480 --> 00:37:28.010
sense of warmth
a little bit.

00:37:28.010 --> 00:37:33.049
You have something that's kind of a little
bit funny and then something that's kind of

00:37:33.049 --> 00:37:35.529
a nod to the
neighborhood and something that's a nod to

00:37:35.529 --> 00:37:36.529
the cuisine.

00:37:36.529 --> 00:37:37.529
I

00:37:37.529 --> 00:37:42.279
just put all that together in a random type
of way to

00:37:42.279 --> 00:37:45.239
help tell the story of the place which most
people never

00:37:45.239 --> 00:37:46.239
notice really.

00:37:46.239 --> 00:37:49.979
It just kind of helps tell the story
really.

00:37:49.979 --> 00:37:51.130
&gt;&gt;Female #3: Hi.

00:37:51.130 --> 00:37:52.279
How are you?

00:37:52.279 --> 00:37:54.359
&gt;&gt; Andrew: How are you doing?

00:37:54.359 --> 00:37:55.920
&gt;&gt; Female #3: Good.

00:37:55.920 --> 00:38:01.349
I was wondering, after listening to your story
about your experience at ElBulli, spending

00:38:01.349 --> 00:38:04.829
the entire day
in the kitchen, learning, talking about food

00:38:04.829 --> 00:38:08.910
if you could
have a similar experience today with anyone

00:38:08.910 --> 00:38:11.489
who would you
spend a day the kitchen with learning and

00:38:11.489 --> 00:38:13.329
collaborating with.

00:38:13.329 --> 00:38:22.720
&gt;&gt; Andrew: You know, I think I'd love to go
to -- I don't know if

00:38:22.720 --> 00:38:25.410
it necessarily would be a chef.

00:38:25.410 --> 00:38:29.589
I'd love to go to Japan
and fish, I think, is what the next thing

00:38:29.589 --> 00:38:31.289
I'd like to do.

00:38:31.289 --> 00:38:35.309
I want to get on a -- I want to see what fishing
is in

00:38:35.309 --> 00:38:36.309
Japan.

00:38:36.309 --> 00:38:44.079
Because seeing -- Japan, it's such an amazing
place to eat and I think I'd like to go on

00:38:44.079 --> 00:38:47.369
a boat and
catch some octopus with like a Japanese -- and

00:38:47.369 --> 00:38:48.369
I have
that connection.

00:38:48.369 --> 00:38:50.000
I've established the connection.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:55.210
They're in a town called Atami and it's -- the
brother of

00:38:55.210 --> 00:38:58.349
a cute Japanese girl that cuts my hair.

00:38:58.349 --> 00:39:04.170
[laughter]And I am going
to -- next time I go to Japan maybe the end

00:39:04.170 --> 00:39:07.200
of next year
I am going octopus fishing with her brother.

00:39:07.200 --> 00:39:10.940
[laughter] I'd like to
find out where things come from and what their

00:39:10.940 --> 00:39:11.940
process
is.

00:39:11.940 --> 00:39:13.269
&gt;&gt; Female #4: Hi.

00:39:13.269 --> 00:39:14.719
How are you.

00:39:14.719 --> 00:39:16.069
I have three questions.

00:39:16.069 --> 00:39:18.450
&gt;&gt; Andrew: We'll charge you extra.

00:39:18.450 --> 00:39:21.329
[laughter]
&gt;&gt; Female #4: My first is what's your favorite

00:39:21.329 --> 00:39:22.700
pizza place in New
York.

00:39:22.700 --> 00:39:24.249
&gt;&gt; Andrew: Favorite pizza.

00:39:24.249 --> 00:39:27.160
You know, pizza is funny.

00:39:27.160 --> 00:39:29.539
Pizza --
people have a lot of love and a lot of hate

00:39:29.539 --> 00:39:30.710
for pizza.

00:39:30.710 --> 00:39:33.819
It's all about the pizza they grew up with
and the pizza

00:39:33.819 --> 00:39:35.890
in their neighborhood.

00:39:35.890 --> 00:39:39.339
I like Motorino . I like that
style pie.

00:39:39.339 --> 00:39:41.890
Keste is good, also.

00:39:41.890 --> 00:39:47.799
But if I want to get a
slice up by Columbia, La Familia is fine because

00:39:47.799 --> 00:39:49.789
it's a
slice joint.

00:39:49.789 --> 00:39:51.549
That's a New York phenomenon.

00:39:51.549 --> 00:39:55.839
So I, I'll
enjoy one of those, too.

00:39:55.839 --> 00:39:57.740
But there's no excuse for bad
pizza.

00:39:57.740 --> 00:40:00.950
[audience chuckles] There's absolutely no
excuse for that.

00:40:00.950 --> 00:40:01.950
So
Motorino.

00:40:01.950 --> 00:40:03.229
I like that Neapolitan style.

00:40:03.229 --> 00:40:04.759
I really like.

00:40:04.759 --> 00:40:09.239
&gt;&gt; Female #4: Question No. 2 -- what's your
favorite ingredient to

00:40:09.239 --> 00:40:13.900
use and how do you feel about flavored oils
and vinegars.

00:40:13.900 --> 00:40:18.499
&gt;&gt; Andrew: Favorite ingredient to use probably
tomatoes just in

00:40:18.499 --> 00:40:19.499
general.

00:40:19.499 --> 00:40:22.300
So much you can do with that and sweet and
sour

00:40:22.300 --> 00:40:27.979
and sauce bases and many cuisines.

00:40:27.979 --> 00:40:33.069
Flavored oils,
flavored vinegars not a big fan.

00:40:33.069 --> 00:40:38.180
Vinegar is -- good
vinegar there's no replacing good vinegar.

00:40:38.180 --> 00:40:41.339
Even like red
wine vinegar to have a good quality like aged

00:40:41.339 --> 00:40:43.410
French
vinegar usually.

00:40:43.410 --> 00:40:46.380
We were making our own vinegar for
awhile which was kind of like a interesting

00:40:46.380 --> 00:40:51.640
experiment
that led to lots of mold and sometimes flies.

00:40:51.640 --> 00:40:55.180
[laughter] But
sometimes those results -- actually cider

00:40:55.180 --> 00:40:59.420
vinegar is
really easy to make at home.

00:40:59.420 --> 00:41:00.569
It's really easy to make at
home.

00:41:00.569 --> 00:41:03.910
If you get a small barrel and some cider you
can

00:41:03.910 --> 00:41:05.849
have some good results with that.

00:41:05.849 --> 00:41:09.410
Flavored oils.

00:41:09.410 --> 00:41:11.979
There's like chemicals involved and it's not.

00:41:11.979 --> 00:41:15.640
You can
get better results just combining those two

00:41:15.640 --> 00:41:16.849
ingredients
by themselves.

00:41:16.849 --> 00:41:17.960
&gt;&gt; Female #4: Right.

00:41:17.960 --> 00:41:22.089
And in terms of marinating red meat, some
chefs don't really believe in that.

00:41:22.089 --> 00:41:26.739
Some will just do it
marinate it for hours some will just throw

00:41:26.739 --> 00:41:27.739
it on the
grill.

00:41:27.739 --> 00:41:29.220
How do you feel about that.

00:41:29.220 --> 00:41:35.579
&gt;&gt;Andrew: It depends what the
application is really if you're going to -- like,

00:41:35.579 --> 00:41:37.410
in the
book, in American flavor, we have -- there's

00:41:37.410 --> 00:41:42.720
a rib recipe
that you put the spices all over the ribs

00:41:42.720 --> 00:41:45.749
and then you
put it in the fridge for six hours.

00:41:45.749 --> 00:41:49.339
That is a certain
application because it's the way we're going

00:41:49.339 --> 00:41:51.469
to cook it
afterwards.

00:41:51.469 --> 00:41:52.760
If you're going to -- it just depends.

00:41:52.760 --> 00:41:54.170
Depends on the cut, too.

00:41:54.170 --> 00:41:56.559
&gt;&gt; Male: What if it's a 16 ounce rib eye.

00:41:56.559 --> 00:42:01.029
I ask because I've heard both sides.

00:42:01.029 --> 00:42:04.289
&gt;&gt; Andrew: 16 ounce rib eye?

00:42:04.289 --> 00:42:07.270
You know, again, I wouldn't
marinate it.

00:42:07.270 --> 00:42:10.819
If you have a great -- if you have a great
piece of meat like that.

00:42:10.819 --> 00:42:15.450
I don't know, you went to
somewhere and sourced something that's really

00:42:15.450 --> 00:42:18.829
great, I'd
rather like it to be beefy.

00:42:18.829 --> 00:42:24.309
At the restaurant, at the
Dutch, I just feel like if I want to open

00:42:24.309 --> 00:42:27.670
up an American
restaurant we had to make it would be pretentious

00:42:27.670 --> 00:42:30.980
of me
not to make the best steak we could.

00:42:30.980 --> 00:42:34.630
So we spend a lot
of time trying to source from a particular

00:42:34.630 --> 00:42:41.559
farm and we
were dry aging for 28 days and we're doing

00:42:41.559 --> 00:42:43.160
this technique
called re-aging.

00:42:43.160 --> 00:42:49.430
Because you dry age the whole piece of meat
and

00:42:49.430 --> 00:42:51.690
then you cut your steaks, you trim it up and
then you cut

00:42:51.690 --> 00:42:52.690
your steaks.

00:42:52.690 --> 00:42:58.930
We cut the steaks and we're aging the
steaks individually again afterwards.

00:42:58.930 --> 00:43:03.400
So there's more dry age
flavor on them.

00:43:03.400 --> 00:43:04.890
It's just salt and pepper.

00:43:04.890 --> 00:43:08.400
So it's kind
of about the natural minerality of the steaks

00:43:08.400 --> 00:43:11.160
and getting
a really good char on the outside instead

00:43:11.160 --> 00:43:15.130
of trying to infuse it with
other flavors.

00:43:15.130 --> 00:43:18.940
I don't think there's a reason to do a
chili rubbed steak necessarily if you have

00:43:18.940 --> 00:43:19.940
a great piece of
meat.

00:43:19.940 --> 00:43:28.489
If I'm going to eat a piece of steak, do
steak [laughter], I want to taste the beefiness

00:43:28.489 --> 00:43:32.309
of it instead of
trying to make it taste like something else.

00:43:32.309 --> 00:43:35.190
With steak
I try to be kind of pure about it.

00:43:35.190 --> 00:43:36.960
&gt;&gt; Female#4: Thank you.

00:43:36.960 --> 00:43:39.910
&gt;&gt;Andrew: Cheers
&gt;&gt; Female #5: Hi.

00:43:39.910 --> 00:43:43.380
So I have a question about the business end
of

00:43:43.380 --> 00:43:44.380
things.

00:43:44.380 --> 00:43:47.260
I mean, it's obvious you go on the reputation
of

00:43:47.260 --> 00:43:48.329
your talent as well.

00:43:48.329 --> 00:43:52.880
But you're also in a very
competitive restaurant market in New York

00:43:52.880 --> 00:43:53.880
City.

00:43:53.880 --> 00:43:55.299
So I
think conventional wisdom always says it's

00:43:55.299 --> 00:43:57.670
one of the
hardest businesses to go into.

00:43:57.670 --> 00:44:01.859
So what do you think
aside from the buzz you get as a chef and

00:44:01.859 --> 00:44:05.789
kind of your
talents what else do you do to run a successful

00:44:05.789 --> 00:44:06.789
operation.

00:44:06.789 --> 00:44:11.489
&gt;&gt; Andrew: It is true, you know, that the
art of cooking is very

00:44:11.489 --> 00:44:13.950
different than the business of food.

00:44:13.950 --> 00:44:16.430
It's like very
very -- they're different.

00:44:16.430 --> 00:44:20.390
And there's no road map to
success.

00:44:20.390 --> 00:44:23.770
No one ever taught me how to do that.

00:44:23.770 --> 00:44:26.460
No one
ever -- there's no book on it.

00:44:26.460 --> 00:44:27.979
They don't teach you that
in school.

00:44:27.979 --> 00:44:32.050
There's no -- it's a lot of mistakes I made.

00:44:32.050 --> 00:44:34.019
I made so many mistakes.

00:44:34.019 --> 00:44:37.210
The thing about mistakes I make
ten a day but I try not to let everyone know

00:44:37.210 --> 00:44:38.210
about them.

00:44:38.210 --> 00:44:40.569
[audience chuckles]
Cover your tracks.

00:44:40.569 --> 00:44:43.190
It's a very human business.

00:44:43.190 --> 00:44:45.619
I have
two operating partners.

00:44:45.619 --> 00:44:49.279
One guy who is a -- we cooked
together for many years.

00:44:49.279 --> 00:44:54.679
He was a chef for me and a cook
for me for many years who has now moved into

00:44:54.679 --> 00:44:59.329
-- he takes
care of the kitchen design and scheduling,

00:44:59.329 --> 00:45:00.329
costing,
organizing.

00:45:00.329 --> 00:45:05.650
He builds the restaurants and then I have
another guy, Josh Picard, who takes care of

00:45:05.650 --> 00:45:09.660
the front end
of the business part of it so I can concentrate

00:45:09.660 --> 00:45:13.940
on what
I'm good at or at least what I aspire to be

00:45:13.940 --> 00:45:15.079
good at.

00:45:15.079 --> 00:45:21.420
And
I think that, again, it's like we can have

00:45:21.420 --> 00:45:25.099
all the opening
buzz you want for a restaurant but that only

00:45:25.099 --> 00:45:28.440
works for
three months, four months and then it's -- you

00:45:28.440 --> 00:45:31.839
have to be
consistent in what you do and I think that's

00:45:31.839 --> 00:45:33.200
really the
biggest thing.

00:45:33.200 --> 00:45:39.279
Doesn't matter if -- if you're the diner
on the corner and you do the dried out grilled

00:45:39.279 --> 00:45:42.339
piece of
chicken on top of the Caesar salad, you want

00:45:42.339 --> 00:45:44.099
to go back
because that's the thing you want to go back

00:45:44.099 --> 00:45:45.329
for.

00:45:45.329 --> 00:45:47.640
It's like the same, every single time.

00:45:47.640 --> 00:45:50.390
So it
doesn't matter if you're doing fois gras three

00:45:50.390 --> 00:45:53.969
ways or pork buns or a bowl of spaghetti or
you're doing the dried

00:45:53.969 --> 00:45:57.940
out piece of chicken, you have to be like
the same and try

00:45:57.940 --> 00:46:00.719
to deliver the same kind of experience.

00:46:00.719 --> 00:46:04.009
And I think
that's the most important thing.

00:46:04.009 --> 00:46:06.049
&gt;&gt; Female #5: Thank you.

00:46:06.049 --> 00:46:08.599
&gt;&gt; Interviewer: Any other questions, guys?

00:46:08.599 --> 00:46:12.810
You need to go to the mic
Matthew.

00:46:12.810 --> 00:46:15.400
[laughter]
&gt;&gt; Andrew: Maybe you should rap.

00:46:15.400 --> 00:46:17.579
&gt;&gt; [laughter] Go ahead.

00:46:17.579 --> 00:46:23.059
&gt;&gt; female #6: So I just have this perception
of chefs always making

00:46:23.059 --> 00:46:25.900
the perfect meal every single time never any
flaws.

00:46:25.900 --> 00:46:28.759
&gt;&gt; Andrew: Oh, that's not a perception -- that's
how it is.

00:46:28.759 --> 00:46:34.930
&gt;&gt; Female #6: But have you as a chef put some
things together how

00:46:34.930 --> 00:46:37.200
much is supposed to go together and then just
say, "oh,

00:46:37.200 --> 00:46:38.200
this is awful."

00:46:38.200 --> 00:46:40.310
And just throw it away and start over.

00:46:40.310 --> 00:46:43.030
&gt;&gt; Andrew: That happens all the time.

00:46:43.030 --> 00:46:45.039
&gt;&gt; Female #6: That's good to know.

00:46:45.039 --> 00:46:46.390
&gt;&gt; Andrew: that happens all the time.

00:46:46.390 --> 00:46:51.890
Just for when the --
usually my process is I'll probably have -- if

00:46:51.890 --> 00:46:54.799
we're
going to do a menu change or we're going to

00:46:54.799 --> 00:46:56.430
come up with
a new restaurant like we just did with The

00:46:56.430 --> 00:47:00.220
Dutch probably
four or five pages of ideas.

00:47:00.220 --> 00:47:05.910
You know, the type on the
computer will be just like local something

00:47:05.910 --> 00:47:07.270
something with
garlic.

00:47:07.270 --> 00:47:10.359
Hey, let's do something with veal ribs.

00:47:10.359 --> 00:47:14.299
Or, you
know, they end up being not -- you have just

00:47:14.299 --> 00:47:17.089
like whittle
down the ideas, kind of.

00:47:17.089 --> 00:47:23.209
And my formula is if one out of
five ideas work, then you had a good day.

00:47:23.209 --> 00:47:26.950
So just kind of
have to like -- sometimes, you know, it sounds

00:47:26.950 --> 00:47:32.630
really
good and "let's try this thing" -- but, you

00:47:32.630 --> 00:47:34.779
know, maybe you
can't get a supply of it every day which happens

00:47:34.779 --> 00:47:36.069
sometimes.

00:47:36.069 --> 00:47:41.820
Or maybe I can make it awesome but then you
try to put it in the production of the restaurant

00:47:41.820 --> 00:47:44.960
making
it every day and it never works because making

00:47:44.960 --> 00:47:49.069
one thing
and making 150 of something it's a different

00:47:49.069 --> 00:47:50.069
context.

00:47:50.069 --> 00:47:52.510
&gt;&gt; Female #6: Thanks.

00:47:52.510 --> 00:47:55.089
&gt;&gt; Male #1: Hi.

00:47:55.089 --> 00:47:57.839
So I sort of -- like, when I go out to eat,
I

00:47:57.839 --> 00:47:59.809
sort of differentiate between the times when
I go out to

00:47:59.809 --> 00:48:02.959
eat and I'm starving and I just want a burger
and fries

00:48:02.959 --> 00:48:07.339
versus something where on a Saturday night
and I've been planning all week to go to a

00:48:07.339 --> 00:48:08.339
restaurant.

00:48:08.339 --> 00:48:11.140
And I just want to know if you have a
thought there were any sort of tips or hard

00:48:11.140 --> 00:48:13.489
and fast
rules to ordering to sort of get the most

00:48:13.489 --> 00:48:17.069
out of your
restaurant experience whether it's ordering

00:48:17.069 --> 00:48:20.150
thematically
or balancing.

00:48:20.150 --> 00:48:27.099
&gt;&gt;Andrew: I think it's all about context and
where you are and

00:48:27.099 --> 00:48:29.749
what type of restaurant it is or who you're
out with or

00:48:29.749 --> 00:48:31.180
what the purpose is.

00:48:31.180 --> 00:48:34.279
Like, obviously you're just eating
to eat, you're going to get a turkey wrap

00:48:34.279 --> 00:48:35.829
and you're
going to split, you know?

00:48:35.829 --> 00:48:43.200
I think that, you know, just
the restaurateur chef in me, any restaurant

00:48:43.200 --> 00:48:45.180
is going to
give.

00:48:45.180 --> 00:48:48.819
I never judge a place on one try.

00:48:48.819 --> 00:48:53.309
Because I know,
as a diner, just eating out so much in all

00:48:53.309 --> 00:48:56.729
of the world,
you can be having the meal of your lifetime

00:48:56.729 --> 00:48:58.980
and the
person next to you can be having the worst

00:48:58.980 --> 00:49:00.849
experience
ever.

00:49:00.849 --> 00:49:03.440
It's just kind of -- it's just the theater
of a

00:49:03.440 --> 00:49:04.440
restaurant.

00:49:04.440 --> 00:49:11.469
And so, I think the thing is, you know --
you know there's obvious.

00:49:11.469 --> 00:49:16.380
On some menus you can just
look at that and that's just wrong I'm going

00:49:16.380 --> 00:49:18.960
to stay away
from that.

00:49:18.960 --> 00:49:21.119
And then, there's the obvious choices.

00:49:21.119 --> 00:49:22.910
Kind
of just depends on how many times you've been

00:49:22.910 --> 00:49:23.910
there.

00:49:23.910 --> 00:49:24.910
Depends on the mood you're in.

00:49:24.910 --> 00:49:29.690
That's why what I try to
do is always balance out the menu so there's

00:49:29.690 --> 00:49:32.630
a little
something kind of for everyone.

00:49:32.630 --> 00:49:37.509
So I have tripe on my
menu but I also have a quinoa salad with squash

00:49:37.509 --> 00:49:38.900
and hazel
nuts.

00:49:38.900 --> 00:49:42.170
It just depends what night it is.

00:49:42.170 --> 00:49:44.510
So if you're
balling with like your buddies and you're

00:49:44.510 --> 00:49:48.369
doing tequila
shots or did you go for the '82 Bordeaux?

00:49:48.369 --> 00:49:49.519
Kind of depends.

00:49:49.519 --> 00:49:52.049
&gt;&gt; Male #1: Just go with your gut.

00:49:52.049 --> 00:49:55.699
&gt;&gt;Andrew: Yeah, just go with your gut
&gt;&gt; Male #1: Thank you.

00:49:55.699 --> 00:49:58.829
&gt;&gt; Male #2: So I guess this is a little bit
related to how you as

00:49:58.829 --> 00:50:01.009
a chef, you know, dine out.

00:50:01.009 --> 00:50:06.539
I think all of us that dine
out a lot you, end up with your pet peeves.

00:50:06.539 --> 00:50:09.410
Just curious
what drives you nuts as a diner.

00:50:09.410 --> 00:50:15.650
&gt;&gt; Andrew: I think the biggest thing is just
not caring.

00:50:15.650 --> 00:50:20.579
That's -- it doesn't matter if it's the Greek
salad.

00:50:20.579 --> 00:50:24.549
It's just blatantly not giving a shit [laughter]
is really kind of

00:50:24.549 --> 00:50:27.670
like the -- that's the thing that like, always.

00:50:27.670 --> 00:50:29.059
Again,
mistakes are going to happen.

00:50:29.059 --> 00:50:34.119
Someone's going to, you
know, they're going to open up their oyster

00:50:34.119 --> 00:50:36.809
and there's
going to be a little sand in it.

00:50:36.809 --> 00:50:37.809
There's too much salt
in it.

00:50:37.809 --> 00:50:42.109
That's going to happen; that's the human aspect
of it.

00:50:42.109 --> 00:50:46.869
Blatant attitude or just
that just like drives me crazy.

00:50:46.869 --> 00:50:50.369
And you can feel it
sometimes when you sit down.

00:50:50.369 --> 00:50:53.000
You know, you can feel it
right away.

00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:55.559
So that's the biggest thing -- yeah.

00:50:55.559 --> 00:50:57.289
&gt;&gt; Male #2: Thanks.

00:50:57.289 --> 00:51:01.309
&gt;&gt; Male #3: Who are your favorite green market
suppliers what

00:51:01.309 --> 00:51:04.589
you're taking that winesap out of the walk
in, and where do you like it to

00:51:04.589 --> 00:51:05.900
be from?

00:51:05.900 --> 00:51:11.989
&gt;&gt; Andrew: You know, I've been buying from
the market here since

00:51:11.989 --> 00:51:13.249
I first came to New York.

00:51:13.249 --> 00:51:17.410
And just being, working
restaurants whatever since the early 90s,

00:51:17.410 --> 00:51:22.980
they're usually
there every Wednesday.

00:51:22.980 --> 00:51:28.340
You know, Franca at Berried
Treasures, we buy a lot from Franca and we

00:51:28.340 --> 00:51:33.859
buy a lot from
Rick Bishop.

00:51:33.859 --> 00:51:36.400
Fortunate enough that I don't have to
physically go to the markets to get those

00:51:36.400 --> 00:51:40.920
things because
they're both busy restaurants.

00:51:40.920 --> 00:51:44.819
We pay cash to the
farmers [chuckles] and so they like to deliver

00:51:44.819 --> 00:51:48.430
to us.

00:51:48.430 --> 00:51:54.539
But
Millerelli, Franca, Berried Treasures, those

00:51:54.539 --> 00:51:57.180
are kind of like
our 'go to' people.

00:51:57.180 --> 00:52:01.599
And then, we have like one or two that
could get us just stuff that they don't even

00:52:01.599 --> 00:52:04.989
put out at
the green market because they know we're going

00:52:04.989 --> 00:52:06.959
to sell it right
away or that's what I want.

00:52:06.959 --> 00:52:10.680
Like someone's going to bring us local chanterelles
the one month they're in season.

00:52:10.680 --> 00:52:13.690
Or
local huckleberries the one month in season.

00:52:13.690 --> 00:52:17.380
I've always
bought a lot from the market even though I

00:52:17.380 --> 00:52:21.229
don't necessarily use that
as a marketing plan.

00:52:21.229 --> 00:52:25.650
It's kind of like, I think, if you're
a good American chef or just a good chef in

00:52:25.650 --> 00:52:28.219
general
that's what you're doing these days.

00:52:28.219 --> 00:52:29.219
Good.

00:52:29.219 --> 00:52:30.789
&gt;&gt; Male #3: Thank you.

